-- ── btunnel ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$btunnel is a lightweight HTTP and TCP reverse-proxy tunneling tool that lets developers expose a local server, file directory, or app running on their own computer to the public internet through a secure, always-HTTPS URL, generated instantly with a single command. It is a small, niche product in the ngrok-style tunneling category, positioned as a lower-cost alternative for common developer needs such as testing webhooks from third-party services, demoing a work-in-progress site to a client, or sharing local files quickly. btunnel ships as a downloadable command-line binary available for multiple operating systems, and its distinguishing features include a built-in file server for sharing local directories without extra configuration, basic authentication protection on tunneled URLs, custom request and response headers, and a web-based UI for monitoring incoming requests in real time. Public information about the company behind btunnel is limited; it appears to be a small, self-funded or bootstrapped product (it launched on Product Hunt around 2023) reportedly based in Bangalore, India, rather than a large, well-documented company, so prospective users should treat headcount, funding, and long-term roadmap details as unverified beyond what is published on its own website.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Freemium (free plan with limits, low-cost paid plan)$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free plan available; paid plan starts at approximately 4.2 dollars per month$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2023, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$1-10 employees (small, independently run product; exact team size not publicly documented)$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$Reportedly Bangalore, Karnataka, India (unverified beyond limited third-party listings)$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$btunnel Review 2026: Localhost Tunneling Tool Features and Pricing$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$btunnel is a low-cost reverse-proxy tool for exposing localhost to the internet over HTTPS. See its features, pricing, and how it compares to alternatives.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$btunnel is a command-line tunneling utility that solves a common developer problem: making something running on your own laptop or local network, such as a web app in development, a webhook receiver, or a folder of files, reachable from anywhere on the internet without deploying it to a server first. It works as an HTTP and TCP reverse proxy, meaning it establishes an outbound connection from your machine to btunnel's servers, which then forward incoming public traffic back to your local port. The result is an instantly generated, HTTPS-protected public URL that anyone can use to reach whatever you are running locally, without you needing to configure port forwarding, firewall rules, or a domain name. This category of tool is best known through ngrok, and btunnel positions itself as a lower-cost alternative aimed at the same core developer workflows: testing webhooks from services like Stripe or GitHub against a local development server, sharing an in-progress site or prototype with a client or teammate for quick feedback, or temporarily exposing a local API for a remote collaborator to hit. Functionally, btunnel distinguishes itself with a few specific features beyond basic tunneling. It includes a built-in file server, so a local directory of files can be shared publicly without spinning up a separate web server first. It supports basic authentication, letting users password-protect a tunnel so that only people with credentials can access it, which matters for sharing anything sensitive or unfinished. It allows custom request and response headers to be set on tunneled traffic, useful for testing scenarios that depend on specific header behavior. And it provides a web-based UI for monitoring requests coming through the tunnel in real time, similar to ngrok's local inspection dashboard, which helps with debugging webhook payloads or API calls as they arrive. The tool is distributed as a downloadable command-line binary for multiple operating systems (users download an appropriately packaged archive, extract it, and run the executable from a terminal or command prompt). On pricing, btunnel offers a free plan that includes HTTPS tunnels, the file server, custom headers, the web monitoring UI, basic auth, and randomly assigned subdomains or geo-location-based URLs, but with a 2-hour session timeout and an interstitial warning page shown to visitors before they reach the tunneled content - both common limitations in this product category meant to push sustained or serious users toward a paid plan. That paid plan is priced at roughly 4.2 dollars per month and removes the session timeout and interstitial page, adds support for TCP tunnels on arbitrary local ports (not just HTTP traffic), and allows registering up to 10 custom subdomains under one account. It is worth being direct about the limits of what is publicly verifiable here: btunnel appears to be a small, relatively new, and likely bootstrapped or self-funded product rather than a large or well-documented company. It launched on Product Hunt around 2023, and while some third-party listings associate it with Bangalore, India, there is no well-corroborated public information about its founding team, company structure, or funding history, so those details should be treated as reported rather than confirmed.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '707c21c2-77d0-4aa8-a1f3-817320f58c18';

